  "reasoning": "The system of congruences modulo m = n+1, along with the condition that n = 2a+6b, leads to equations: 3a+5b = 19 + p(2a+6b+1) and 4a+2b = 25 + q(2a+6b+1). Solving for positive integers a, b, p, q yields a = 27, b = 7, with p = q = 1, so m = 97 and n = 96. Then ℓ = m - 95 = 2. The quadrilateral ABCD has sides AB = 2, BC = 3, CD = 5, DA = 4, satisfying AB + CD = BC + DA = 7, so it is tangential. The inradius r satisfies Area = r * s, where s = 7. To maximize r, maximize Area. The maximum area for given sides occurs when the quadrilateral is cyclic, and by Brahmagupta's formula, Area_max = √((s-2)(s-3)(s-5)(s-4)) = √120 = 2√30. Thus r_max = Area_max / s = 2√30/7.",
